I have tested this bug in two WinXP system, and their locale both are Chinese, but there is no problem in Win2000 system with Chinese locale of one machine. First ICU are installed correctly since we are using the plugin attached by Eclipse3.2M4. Secondly this bug might belong to ICU. Below test can be simply to test whether this bug exists in a specified platform.

public class TestICU
{
	public static void main( String[] argv )
	{
		SimpleDateFormat sm_dateFormat = new SimpleDateFormat( "yyyyMMdd-HHmmss" );
		System.out.println( sm_dateFormat.toString( ) );
	}

}

It seems that com.ibm.icu.util.ZoneMeta.getSystemTimeZone(String) method has a bug. It cannot handle GMT-offset-based time zone ID with format like "GMT+8:00"(meanwhile it does manage to handle some other kinds of timezone id, say, "GMT", or "Asia/Shanghai".This will in turn possibly lead to a NPE.

The following is the code of problem in com.ibm.icu.util.TimeZone class.

    public static synchronized TimeZone getDefault() {
        if (defaultZone == null) {
            //The following line get a TimeZone instance which may possiblility have 
            //a GMT-offset-based time zone ID 
            java.util.TimeZone temp=java.util.TimeZone.getDefault();

            //The calling of ZoneMeta.getSystemTimeZone(temp.getID())
            //will then return a null value.
            defaultZone = ZoneMeta.getSystemTimeZone(temp.getID());
        }
        //The null pointer exception is thrown out here.
        return (TimeZone) defaultZone.clone();
    }

As far as I know, in some windows XP environment java.util.TimeZone.getDefault() method will return TimeZone instances with GMT-offset-based time zone ID (On the other hand, I do find that in some XP and windows 2000 environment the method will return time zone ID with format like "Asia/Shanghai".In that case the com.ibm.icu.util.TimeZone.getDefault() method works fine). 

This problem has been logged to ICU support mailist.
